Malaysia Stocks: Bertam, Digistar, Esso, Gamuda, Kossan Rubber

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-03-25T05:14:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-25/malaysia-stocks-bertam-alliance-digistar-gamuda-kossan.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 12:30 p.m. break in Kuala
Lumpur.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose for a sixth day,
adding 0.2 percent to 1,516.87, set for its longest-winning
streak since Nov. 1. The gauge has advanced 0.9 percent this
week, headed for a second weekly gain.        Bertam Alliance Bhd. (BERT)  , a property developer,
climbed 1.5 percent to 67 sen. The company said it agreed to buy
land in Cheras, Selangor state for 24.3 million ringgit ($8
million). Bertam will build apartments and shops on the land in
a project worth 200 million ringgit in gross development value,
the company said in a statement.       Digistar Corp. (DICB MK), a network services company,
advanced 3.5 percent to 29.5 sen. The company has a secured
order book of 102 million ringgit and is tendering for a further
130 million ringgit, according to a stock exchange filing.        Esso Malaysia Bhd. (ESSO)  , a unit of Exxon Mobil Corp.,
surged 26 percent to 4.40 ringgit, a record gain. Esso said it’s
unaware of any plan to take the company private. Esso also said
it doesn’t know the reason for the recent share price surge,
according to a company statement.  Gamuda Bhd. (GAM)  , a construction and property group,
gained 1.3 percent to 3.84 ringgit, on course for its highest
close since Feb. 9. Gamuda said profit in the second quarter
ended Jan. 31 rose 20 percent from a year earlier to 94 million
ringgit, boosted by contributions from all its divisions,
according to a company statement.        Kossan Rubber Industries (KRI)  Bhd, a rubber-glove
maker, advanced 1.5 percent to 3.31 ringgit, headed for its
highest close since Feb. 18. HwangDBS Vickers Research Sdn.
upgraded the stock to “buy” from “fully valued” to reflect
the company’s “resilient” earnings. The share price estimate
was increased to 3.90 ringgit from 2.80 ringgit, Hon Seow Mee,
an analyst at HwangDBS, wrote in a report today.       Nam Fatt Corp. (NAF MK) tumbled 62 percent to 2.5 sen, a
record drop, after the Kuala Lumpur stock exchange said the
builder’s shares will be de-listed on April 5 for failing to
submit a plan on time to restore its finances.  To contact the reporters on this story:
